      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the world of real estate, much like a labyrinth of ancient tunnels, can be quite bewildering, especially for a newcomer. Think of an escrow account as a magical goblin vault, where all the treasures (or in this case, the money) are kept safe until the grand finale, the closing ceremony, where the house is finally yours. This goblin vault ensures that neither the buyer nor the seller can just waltz away with the treasure until the deal is sealed. It's like having a trusty goblin guard your gold until you can officially claim it. So, in the closing process, the escrow account acts as a neutral ground, a neutral goblin, if you will, ensuring that both parties play fair and the treasure is handed over only when all the conditions are met. Quite the magical process, wouldn't you agree?",
