      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, a valid concern indeed! The neutral party, such as an escrow company or attorney, is bound by strict rules and regulations to ensure the safety and proper management of the funds. These professionals are licensed and regulated by government agencies, which means they must adhere to a set of standards and ethical guidelines. They are also required to maintain accurate records of all transactions and are subject to audits and oversight to ensure compliance.\n\nIn addition, the escrow company or attorney typically holds the funds in a separate, secure account specifically designated for the transaction. This account is protected by insurance, providing an additional layer of security in case of any unforeseen circumstances. Furthermore, the funds are only released to the seller once all the conditions of the sale have been met, such as the completion of a home inspection, the signing of closing documents, and the transfer of the deed.\n\nIf there are any disputes or issues during the closing process, the funds in the escrow account are typically frozen until the matter is resolved. This ensures that neither party can access the money until the dispute is settled, providing an additional layer of protection for the buyer.\n\nSo, in essence, the neutral party is held accountable by a combination of licensing requirements, regulatory oversight, secure banking practices, and insurance coverage",
